<font color="#FF0000">LESSONS AND REDEFINING  </font><br>
<tt>Mon Aug 11  1:47:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Humming Eagle &amp; Arthur,<br><br>
As I write these words, my newly found cat has climbed upon the canoe outside my window, and is swatting moths from my window screen.  The kitten came to us only a few weeks ago, weak and obviously in need of a home.  It had been to the house being constructed across the street, when a neighbor's dog chased it across the road to our home.  My boys liked it, even though it was a pretty scraggly-looking thing.  I found some cat food, and got it a meal.  In the weeks since it has come our way, it has grown, and filled out.  It's coat is now glossy, and it is very loving to us.  We enjoy watching it play, hunting grasshoppers.  And now, it has rewarded us by killing two gophers from our yard.  <br><br>
Like our new cat, these words are feeding many, including myself.  I have not been too active writing here recently as I am in an intensive effort to do just what has been described here, redefine mysely, find meaningful employment, and work to set up a consulting business at the same time.  <br><br>
Part of this process, that of redefining myself, in one which I have been continually doing.  Our daily experiences, and our choices, make us who we are.  As we continue in this life, we meet obsticles and hazards.  How we deal with them defines our existence.  <br><br>
I often canoe on the river close to my home.  I have taken a route which covers the same part of the river, upstream and then back down to my takeout, many times.  But I have never had the exact same experience on any of these trips.  It is a different season, time of the day, and route (I can never take exactly the same route twice of any two trips).  The river itself changes, from the low water in the rain during the fall to the floods of winter to the spring-time snow melt to the summer low, warm water--the river constantly changes.  It renews me to see the same river differently each time.<br><br>
Likewise in life, we can try to travel the same patterns, the same places, but the times have changed.  As on the river, no two of life's obstacles can be faced exactly the same way the next time.<br><br>
But we can learn from our experiences, and apply that knowledge to our next adventures.  I understand the eddies of my river, how to use them to paddle much easier upstream, and in high water how to go very close to the bank to find the stiller water.  This allows me to paddle upstream a considerable distance, even when the water is high. <br><br>
Likewise, I have found wisdom and words of strength here.  I will use this experience to increase my self-confidence, and grow some new seeds.  Thank you.  It is time to lay down, relax my vigilence, and enjoy my family.  I hope that even those who do not participate in these dialogs may draw inner strength, and hope, to help with their next experiences with the world.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


